<MAN>
  <LANGUAGE>eng</LANGUAGE>
  <TITLE> b_split  </TITLE>
  <TYPE>Scilab Function  </TYPE>
  <DATE> May, 2006 </DATE>
  <SHORT_DESCRIPTION name="b_split"> splits one beam into two beams. </SHORT_DESCRIPTION>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>[field_out_1,field_out_2]=b_split(field_in[,split])  </CALLING_SEQUENCE_ITEM>
  </CALLING_SEQUENCE>
  <PARAM>
 <PARAM_INDENT>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>field_in  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
          <SP>:input field. it must be diffractive wavefront. </SP>
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>split  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
          <SP>: the splitting coefficient, split=0.5 if defaulted. </SP>
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>field_out_1  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
          <SP>: the output field whose intensity is sqrt(split) of the field_in</SP>
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_ITEM>
  <PARAM_NAME>field_out_2  </PARAM_NAME>
  <PARAM_DESCRIPTION>
          <SP>: the output field whose intensity is sqrt(1-split) of the field_in</SP>
  </PARAM_DESCRIPTION> 
  </PARAM_ITEM>
 </PARAM_INDENT>
  </PARAM>
  <DESCRIPTION>
  <P>
    <VERB>b_split</VERB> and <VERB>b_mix</VERB> are two commands useful to model 
    interferometers. With <VERB>b_split</VERB> we split the field structure (amplitude division) 
    to two field.<VERB>b_split</VERB> provides the possibility of amplitude division, 
    preserving the sum of intensities of the two splitted beams. The two obtained 
    files could be processed separately and then mixed again with <VERB>b_mix</VERB>.
  </P>
  </DESCRIPTION>
  <EXAMPLE><![CDATA[
	f1=begin(0.005,0.55e-6,512);
	f2=circ_ap(f1,0.00012,-0.0005);
	f3=circ_ap(f1,0.00012,0.0005);
	f4=b_mix(f2,f3);
	f5=forvard(f4,0.75);
	file_ps(f5,"young");
 ]]></EXAMPLE>
